duties:
Provide one-on-one or group support to students in beginning and intermediate French courses. The duties of this position include:
• helping beginning and intermediate students practice their French pronunciation, develop their speaking skills, understand essential grammatical concepts and improve their vocabulary;
• guiding informal and formal conversations in French to help intermediate students improve their spontaneous interactions in French;
• reviewing material learned in class and helping students with questions about grammar and syntax;
• Other duties, as appropriate


Provide 2 hour/ week availability. Duties are completed in-person at UTSC from September 2024 - December 2024.
Schedule to be determined in conjunction with Program Coordinator


Note: The number of hours are an estimate and are tentative pending enrolment numbers.

qualifications_minimum:
In addition to the on-line application, you must submit a writing sample (individually authored and no more than four pages) to Josie Alaimo or email to: josie.alaimo@utoronto.ca
 Current PhD student; 
At least two years' experience as a course TA, whether leading tutorials/ labs, in-class instruction, or grading;
Excellent oral communication and interpersonal skills, particularly the ability to work effectively with and show tact when communicating with administrators, course instructors and TAs;
Strong administrative skills, including ability to schedule meetings and training sessions, plan and document work;
 Strong time management  skills with ability to meet multiple deadlines;
Strong facilitation and presentation skills and/or experience leading/facilitating workshops;
Evidence of superior writing skills in their discipline (writing sample must be individually authored)

duties:
Duties are in person unless otherwise indicated.  All TAs must be available for mandatory in-person weekly meetings on Thursdays 10-11 am. Attend in-person lectures to assist in classroom activities; Prepare for each week by doing online or possibly in-person programming activities. TAs should be available during at least one full set of the seven in-person CSC108 lecture times. L0101: MO 12-1 and WE 11-1; L0201: MO 2-3 and WE 1-3; L0301: MO 3-4 and WE 3-5 ; L0401: TU 9-11 and TH 9-10 ; L0501: TU 11-1 and TH 12-1 ; L0601/L0602:TU 3-5 and TH 3-4; L5201/L5202 TU 6-9. L5101: MO 18-19 and WE 18-20 will be a hybrid section held both online and in-person. To TA for this section, applicants must be able to attend in person for the midterm tests (Oct 7 and Nov 11) and be willing and able to attend online (with their cameras turned on) for all other classes. TAs should have some availability Monday to Friday, 9am to 7pm for in-person office hours. TAs must be available for 5 hours of in-person term test 1 marking Tues Oct 8, Thurs Oct 10, Fri Oct 11 or Tues Oct 15. TAs must be available for 5 hours of in-person term test 2 marking between noon on Tues Nov 12 and 5pm on Fri Nov 15.

Most TA work will involve participation in person (including weekly TA meetings and marking sessions.) TA work done remotely will require a computer on which software such as Python can be installed on (a tablet computer such as a Chromebook or iPad is NOT sufficient) and a reliable high-speed internet connection. For any remote office hours, TAs must be willing and able to participate with their cameras on. May include other tasks, such as monitoring discussion forums.

This course also requires all TAs to be available to mark the final exam in-person. The final exam date is determined by the Faculty of Arts and Science and the exam may be scheduled from Dec. 6-21. The exam schedule is released in November 2024. Every effort will be made to schedule and complete the exam marking within 5-7 business days after the final exam date. There is a small chance TAs may be required to complete grading January 6-8 if the exam is scheduled the last few days of the exam period. The University is closed for the holiday break between December 24, 2024-January 3, 2025;

